a_3.informal problem:
Let $\theta$ be a real number such that $\pi \le \theta < 2\pi$. Define two real numbers $P$ and $Q$ as follows:

$P = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^n}{2^{n+1}} \left\{
  \begin{array}{l l}
    \cos\left(\frac{n+1}{2}\theta\right) & \quad \text{if $n$ is odd}\\
    -\sin\left(\frac{n}{2}\theta\right) & \quad \text{if $n$ is even}
  \end{array} \right.$

$Q = 1 + \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^n}{2^{n+2}} \left\{
  \begin{array}{l l}
    \sin\left(\frac{n+3}{2}\theta\right) & \quad \text{if $n$ is odd}\\
    -\cos\left(\frac{n}{2}\theta\right) & \quad \text{if $n$ is even}
  \end{array} \right.$

If $\frac{P}{Q} = \frac{2\sqrt{2}}{7}$, then find the value of $\sin\theta$. The final answer is $-\frac{17}{19}$.
